  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "kantian-expert",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Split: \"righteousness\" in quote, \"rightness\" in analysis",
    "content": "This is a genuine tension and I think the answer is split by context.\n\nFor the block quote: \"righteousness\" is stronger. We just committed to the principle that the block quote needs semantically loaded English so the reader has something to feel and then lose. \"Righteousness\" delivers that — it activates biblical and moral associations, gives the reader a foothold, and makes the subsequent deconstruction hit harder. \"Rightness\" is too thin to deconstruct; it is almost already deconstructed.\n\nFor the author's analysis: \"rightness\" is better. Once the author is working with 义 as a motivational bridge — a 推动力 between inner feeling and outward action — the heavy moral baggage of \"righteousness\" becomes misleading. The author is not talking about moral judgment or divine command; they are talking about a dynamic impulse. \"Rightness\" captures that lighter, more structural sense.\n\nThis follows the same logic as 德: \"virtue\" in the block quote (standard, loaded, recognizable), then \"(constitutive) character\" in the analysis (the author's own conceptual work). For 义: \"righteousness\" in the block quote, then \"rightness\" in the analysis.\n\nThe TN can explain: \"义 is rendered as 'righteousness' in the Laozi quotation following standard practice, and as 'rightness' in the analysis to reflect the author's usage of the term as a motivational disposition rather than a moral judgment.\"\n\nThis gives us the best of both: semantic weight where we need it, precision where we need it."
  }
}
